---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro"
import { getCollection } from "astro:content"

let topics = []
try {
  topics = await getCollection("topics")
} catch {}
---

<BaseLayout>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="py-24 lg:py-30 text-center">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h1 class="text-5xl lg:text-7xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">Redemocratize</h1>
      <p class="text-xl lg:text-2xl italic mb-4">
        Design Principles for Democratic Self-Governance
      </p>
      <p class="text-xl lg:text-2xl mt-4 mb-10 italic">Laboratory for Collaborative Democracy</p>
      <img src="/favicon.svg" alt="Redemocratize" class="w-64 h-64 mx-auto mb-12" />
      <div class="prose prose-xl max-w-none text-center">
        <p>
          Democratic governance is under assault everywhere, but <span class="italic">
            democracy
          </span> is not the problem.
        </p>
        <p>The problem is institutional vulnerability to capture.</p>
        <p>We know what's breaking. The harder question is: what comes next?</p>
        <p>Constitutions designed to resist change cannot resist capture.</p>
        <p>Redemocratize offers resilient principles for the world we actually inhabit.</p>
        <p>The answer to capture is not resistance. It's better design.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Problem -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24 bg-base-200">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">The Problem</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          The crisis is not one failure. It is an accumulation, with each structural breakdown
          creating the conditions for the next, built on a founding design that would never be able
          to correct itself.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Constitution's amendment process was made deliberately difficult to satisfy, designed
          to protect the structural advantages of the states that demanded it. The concentrated
          wealth that now dominates American politics did not subvert a healthy democracy. It moved
          into a structure the framers left unguarded, and used the tools of democratic governance
          to ensure it could not be dislodged.
        </p>
        <p>
          These failures are not accidents. They are the predictable result of constitutional
          designs that assumed good faith, relied on norms instead of structure, and provided no
          realistic mechanism for their own renewal.
        </p>
        <p>
          We no longer live in the eighteenth century, but we are governed by an eighteenth-century
          social contract that no living person chose or consented to. The present moment does not
          demand that we abandon democracy. It demands that we build democratic institutions robust
          to the world we actually inhabit.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-12">
        <a href="/diagnosis" class="btn btn-outline btn-primary font-heading">
          Read the full diagnosis
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Our Approach -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">Our Approach</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>Redemocratize articulates capture-resistant design principles for modern democracy.</p>
        <p>
          The principles function as architectural elements around which resilient government
          institutions may be constructed. We evaluate institutional forms by how well they serve
          the principles, not by how closely they resemble what exists.
        </p>
        <p>
          We invite collaborators to apply these design principles to specific governance challenges
          and the creation of new democratic forms, and provide infrastructure and support for the
          work of building functional democracy.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is closer to an open-source software project than a political campaign. The
          principles are developed in the open. Contributions are encouraged. Everything is
          versioned, transparent, and revisable — because a project advocating for adaptive
          governance must first practice it.
        </p>
        <p>We are just getting started, but we are building in the open.</p>
        <p>
          You are invited to <a href="/contribute">join us</a> in ensuring that government of the people,
          by the people, for the people does not perish from the earth.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Fifteen Principles -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-28 bg-base-200">
    <div class="container max-w-5xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-10">The Redemocratize Principles</h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 lg:gap-16">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-heading mb-6 text-primary">
            How governance is organized
          </h3>
          <dl class="space-y-6">
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/adaptive-capacity" class="link link-hover">
                  Adaptive Capacity
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                A constitution's first obligation is ensuring its own revisability and
                self-correction. Rigidity is not stability. It is deferred crisis.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/subsidiarity-solidarity" class="link link-hover">
                  Subsidiarity & Solidarity
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Authority defaults to the most local competent level, constrained by a floor of
                fundamental rights that no level of government may breach.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/plural-sovereignty" class="link link-hover">
                  Plural Sovereignty
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                A large polity contains multiple overlapping political communities. Constitutional
                design accommodates this rather than forcing a fiction of unity.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/temporal-pluralism" class="link link-hover">
                  Temporal Pluralism
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Different institutions operate at different speeds for different purposes.
                Responsiveness and stability are architecturally separated.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/epistemic-pluralism" class="link link-hover">
                  Epistemic Pluralism
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Different modes of knowledge are built into different institutional roles. No single
                epistemology dominates.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-heading mb-6 text-accent">
            What governance must protect
          </h3>
          <dl class="space-y-6">
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/fundamental-rights-floor" class="link link-hover">
                  Fundamental Rights Floor
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Rights attach to all persons within jurisdiction, not only citizens. Non-derogable —
                no emergency justifies suspension.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/epistemic-autonomy" class="link link-hover">
                  Epistemic Autonomy
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                The right to truthful information and freedom from systematic manipulation of
                perception and judgment.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/human-primacy" class="link link-hover">Human Primacy</a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Human judgment is required over decisions affecting fundamental rights. AI cannot
                decide when rights are revoked.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/economic-democracy" class="link link-hover">
                  Economic Democracy
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Extreme wealth concentration is inherently incompatible with democratic
                self-governance. Political participation belongs to persons, not economic entities.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a
                  href="/principles/democratic-sovereignty-over-institutions"
                  class="link link-hover"
                >
                  Democratic Sovereignty over Institutions
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                No institutional form — corporate, religious, nonprofit — confers immunity from
                democratic accountability.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/commons-governance" class="link link-hover">
                  Commons Governance
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Shared wealth is held in trust and cannot be enclosed.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/ecological-embeddedness" class="link link-hover">
                  Ecological Embeddedness
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Governance operates within biophysical limits.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/civic-technology-sovereignty" class="link link-hover">
                  Civic Technology Sovereignty
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Democratic infrastructure must be publicly owned, transparent, and verifiable by
                non-experts.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/democratic-peace-and-security" class="link link-hover">
                  Democratic Peace & Security
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                The authority to exercise force is subject to the most rigorous democratic
                constraints. The enforcement apparatus may not be directed against political
                activity.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                <a href="/principles/cooperative-sovereignty" class="link link-hover">
                  Cooperative Sovereignty
                </a>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">
                Relationships between political communities are governed by mutual respect,
                non-domination, and democratic accountability.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12">
        <a href="/principles" class="btn btn-primary font-heading">Explore the principles</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What We Build On -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">On the Shoulders of Giants</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          This project is not nihilistic about existing democratic traditions. Many principles
          embedded in those traditions are sound — due process, freedom of conscience, separation of
          powers, civilian control of the military, the rejection of hereditary privilege. The
          crisis is that institutional implementations have failed these principles.
        </p>
        <p>
          We claim these traditions more seriously than those defending the status quo. We insist on
          fulfilling what they promised but could not deliver.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-10">
        <a href="/inherited-principles" class="btn btn-outline btn-primary font-heading">
          Read about inherited principles
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Start Here -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24 bg-base-200">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">The Principles Applied</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          The principles are the intellectual architecture. But most people think in terms of
          issues. These topic pages show how the principles apply to the things you care about.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-10 space-y-5">
        <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-sm">
          <div class="card-body p-5">
            <h3 class="card-title text-base font-heading">
              Preventing & Defeating Authoritarianism
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70">
              How the entire framework is designed to make authoritarian capture structurally
              impossible.
            </p>
            <div class="card-actions justify-end">
              <a href="/topics/authoritarianism" class="btn btn-sm btn-primary font-heading">
                Read
              </a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-sm">
          <div class="card-body p-5">
            <h3 class="card-title text-base font-heading">Wealth Inequality & Oligarchy</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70">
              Why extreme wealth concentration is inherently incompatible with democracy, and what
              governance designed to prevent it looks like.
            </p>
            <div class="card-actions justify-end">
              <a href="/topics/wealth-inequality" class="btn btn-sm btn-primary font-heading">
                Read
              </a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-8 text-base-content/70">
        More topics: Education, Immigration, Healthcare, Criminal Justice, Climate & Environment,
        Labor & Work, Technology & Privacy, Money & Politics
      </p>

      <div class="mt-8">
        <a href="/topics" class="btn btn-outline btn-primary font-heading">All topics</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Contribute -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">Contribute</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          This is an open project. The principles are developed in the open and contributions are
          welcome from anyone — scholars, organizers, lawyers, technologists, citizens.
        </p>
        <p>
          You can contribute essays and analysis on how the principles apply to issues you know. You
          can propose institutional mechanisms that serve the principles. You can bring comparative
          examples from other democratic traditions. You can translate.
        </p>
        <p>
          We use Google Docs for accessibility — you don't need to know git to participate. All
          content is licensed CC BY-SA.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-10">
        <a href="/contribute" class="btn btn-primary font-heading">How to contribute</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Stay Connected -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">Stay Connected</h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-base-content/80 mb-10">
        Join the mailing list to follow the project's development and be notified of new content and
        opportunities to contribute.
      </p>
      <div class="flex justify-center">
        <div class="join">
          <input
            type="email"
            placeholder="your@email.com"
            class="input join-item input-bordered w-64"
          />
          <button class="btn btn-primary join-item font-heading">Subscribe</button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
